\pard\nowidctlpar\b\i\f1 Risus\b0\i0  is a complete Role Playing Game (RPG) designed to provide an "RPG Lite" for those nights when the brain is too tired for exacting detail. Risus is especially valuable to GMs assembling a quick convention game, or any late-night beer-and-pretzels outing. While it is essentially a Universal Comedy System, it works just as well for serious play (if you insist!). Best of all, a Risus character takes about 20 seconds to create!\par
\par
\b CREDIT WHERE IT'S DUE\b0\par
\tab Inspiration for the nature of this game comes largely from the sadly out-of-print classic, \b\i Ghostbusters, \b0\i0 from West End Games, sparked against an idea (Clich\'e9s) from \b\i DC Heroes\b0\i0 . The final shape and form of the game was inspired by \b\i Over the Edge, \b0\i0 from Atlas Games. Other RPGs (most notably \b\i GURPS, FUDGE \b0\i0 and \b\i Tunnels and Trolls\b0\i0 ), have also provided valuable inspiration. Many friends, fellow gamers, total strangers on the street, and others have provided useful commentary as the game has developed, including Dan "Moose" Jasman, Frank J. Perricone, Jason Puckett, David Pulver, Sean "Dr. Kromm" Punch, and the gamers on the Risus internet mailing list.\par
\par
\b\f0\fs32 CHARACTER CREATION!\b0\f1\fs20\par
\par
\tab Characters are defined by Clich\'e9s (sometimes several of them). Clich\'e9s are a shorthand which describe what a character knows how to do. The ``character classes'' of the Neolithic Period of RPGs were Clich\'e9s: Fighter and Magic-User, Space Marine and Star Merchant. You can take Clich\'e9s like that, or choose a more contemporary one, such as Biker, Spy, Computer Nerd, Supermodel, or William Shatner (formerly an actor - now just a Clich\'e9). Which Clich\'e9s are permitted are up to the GM.\par
\tab Clich\'e9s are defined in terms of Dice (by which we mean the ordinary six-sided kind you can scavenge from your old \b\i Yahtzee\b0\i0  set). This is the number of dice that you roll whenever your skill as a Fighter, Supermodel, or William Shatner (for instance) is challenged. See ``Game System,'' below. Three dice is professional. Six dice is mastery. One die is a putz.\par
\tab Characters are created by naming and describing them, and listing their Clich\'e9s. When designing your character, you have 10 dice with which to define his Clich\'e9s (a Normal Schmoe would be built on anywhere from 3 to 5 dice). A straightforward medieval fighter character might look like this:\par
\par
\tab\b Grolfnar Vainsson the Viking\b0\par
\tab\i Description: \i0 Tall, blond, and grinning. Likes to drink\par
\tab\tab      and fight and drink and chase Viking women\par
\tab\tab      and fight and sail the high seas and raid.\par
\tab\tab      Wants to write great sagas about himself.\par
\tab\b Clich\'e9s:\b0  Viking (4), Womanizer (2), Gambler (3), Poet (1)\par
\par
\tab A character may have any number or combination of Clich\'e9s, but more than 10 different Clich\'e9s would be odd, considering the number of dice you get. Characters shouldn't begin their career with more than 4 dice in anything, but just because you're creating a character today doesn't mean that he's beginning his career! The GM will tell you if he's requiring ``beginners'' for the game. It's not our business.\par
\par
